english:
  title: Preface to the Snowy Valley Poetry Manuscript
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How abundantly Heaven has blessed my passion for poetry! In those days when I dwelt in the capital of the Middle Kingdom, I lodged in the home of my neighbor, Magistrate Wu. There I found a collection of the Hundred Poets of Tang, and borrowing half the volumes, I read through them once. From time to time I also obtained the collected works of celebrated ministers and talented scholars of that age, and though I could not fully comprehend their depths and subtleties, they sufficed to bring me joy. When I returned eastward, I carried with me more than a dozen volumes of Tang poetry, hoping to use them to enhance my pleasure during retirement in the mountains. Yet circumstances placed unworthy me in the favor of the throne, and I was given administrative duties that consumed my attention, preventing me from devoting myself wholly to poetry and verse. This grieved me greatly. I also lamented that the writings of our predecessors have been so rarely preserved. How much more so now, after these times of chaos—who among us can still harbor such aspirations?

    Yet I obtained the Manuscript of the Late Ji'an and the Collected Works of Yi Jae, and reading them once dispelled the melancholy that had weighed upon me since coming south. Was this not Heaven's fortune?

    My colleague Zheng Gongquan's father has compiled the works of the late Remonstrant-Gentleman—our predecessor in the family—and titled it the Snowy Valley Poetry Manuscript, comprising two volumes. He has entrusted me with writing this preface. Upon examining the Snowy Valley poems, I find them clear without being austere, elegant without being wanton. Their language and spirit are refined and profound, not deigning to employ even a single vulgar word. Among his finest works, many stand equal to the accomplished ministers and talented scholars I have known in the Middle Kingdom, and if placed alongside the Yao and Xue families of Tang poetry, they would not pale in comparison.

    Alas, what calamity under Heaven could be more dreadful than that bitter winter of the Xin-Chou year? In those times, whether one possessed wisdom or folly, virtue or baseness, all watched helplessly as their household possessions—however essential—vanished in an instant. Even matters of life and death were abandoned without hesitation. What need to speak of these fragile pages, so easily lost and so difficult to preserve? Yet filial duty moved the son to act where I could not dare to promise. Without Gongquan's father, and without Heaven's continued favor toward my love of poetry, how could I have found such joy in this time of upheaval and displacement, to wander freely in verse and fulfill a longtime wish?

    Yet this blessing is not mine alone. When future historians compile the record of literature and the arts, they shall draw evidence from this collection. Should there come one who inherits and continues the tradition of the Ni-shan recluse's East-land anthology, they too shall draw from this collection. Thus will the name of Snowy Valley grow ever brighter with time. And should this manuscript itself endure, it is Gongquan's father we must thank. How fitting it is to say that he has honored his filial duty well!

    Snowy Valley's given name was Seo, his courtesy name Zhongfu. He enjoyed a friendship with my late father, Jiating. I too hold Gongquan's father in great affection, and our shared desire to preserve his ancestor's legacy moves me with gladness to compose this preface.
  footnotes:
    - The Xin-Chou year refers to 1361, marking the turbulent period of Mongol collapse and the rise of the Ming—a time of great upheaval in East Asia.
    - Yao and Xue refer to celebrated Tang poets Yao He and Xue Tao, representing the highest standards of poetic achievement.
    - The 'Ni-shan recluse' and 'East-land anthology' likely reference Korean literary traditions of preserving and classifying earlier poetry.
